<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pleuraphis jamesii </i>is a warm-season, rhizomatous, perennial grass tolerant of arid areas. It is not a prolific seed producer, and seed viability is low. Culms attain heights between 5 and 60 cm. Although rhizomatous, it grows as a bunch grass, and under favorable conditions bunches merge, forming a sod. Underground rhizomes to 2 m constitute most of a plant’s biomass. Plants may persist for 5 to 7 years, and production varies with moisture availability (Simonin 2000c). <i>Hilaria jamesii </i>is another botanical name used for this species. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is restricted in California to the eastern Mojave Desert and southeastern Great Basin in areas with summer precipitation, and it also ranges well into the northern Great Basin and into the Great Plains. In California, the alliance forms small patches in associated stands of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Coleogyne ramosissima, Ericameria nauseosa, Krascheninnikovia lanata, Ephedra nevadensis, Menodora spinescens, </i>and <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>alliances. Climatic conditions are colder for this alliance than for the <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
