    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Aj, Al). Stands occur in the Lanfair Valley, the Mid Hills, and the New York Mountains (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands occur on the mid-elevation slopes of the White Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands in the Panamint Mountains and Deep Springs Valley are generally small (< 5 ha), where they occur on relatively steep slopes adjacent to valley bottoms associated with those of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Grayia spinosa,</i> and <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> alliances. Stands in the Inyo Mountains ascend to 2800 m (Desert Workshop 2000) on relatively steep rocky slopes, often associated with <i>Ephedra nevadensis</i> and <i>Menodora spinescens</i> alliances.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This is a rare alliance in California. Fires are uncommon in the California stands, and grazing appears destructive. Stands in the state contain disturbance-related shrubs and non-native annual grasses including <i>Bromus tectorum</i>. We should identify, monitor, and manage these stands to ensure their long-term protection. </div>
</div>

    

    

